availability.p: For internal use by the Faclair na Gàidhlig/DASG projects

note.p: MS15 mainly consists of an 18th-century duanaire on the Dillon family of Co. Mayo, as well as sundry other material. There in, however, are found folios (fols 57–79) in the hand of Cathal MacMhuirich (fl. 1625), plus one more (fol. 80) in an unidentified hand (Hand59) containing genealogical material on Clan MacLeod. Two poems from Cathal's folios have been transcribed, plus the the MacLeod genealogy. The two poems are thought to be Cathal's own compositions.

Cathal MacMhuirich is regarded as one of the most creative 17th-century Gaelic poets in the Classical tradition from the 17th century. The two poems by him included in the corpus from this manuscript present specimens of verse and prose panegyric (Text 1) and verse satire (Text 2). The MacLeod genealogy (Text 3), meanwhile, is annotated with some intriguing epithets and allusions to otherwise poorly attested episodes in pseudo-history.

summary.p: Texts 1 and 2 are thought to be Cathal MacMhuirich's own compositions, as well as his scribal productions. They exemplify the playfulness for which he is reputed (Black 1976-78), with Text 1 being a bombastic, vividly illustrated praise poem and Text 2 a satire of a sub-standard poet framed sarcastically as a panegyric. This literary interest, combined with Text 1 including both prose and verse, makes them a particularly rich source for Gaelic literary culture at the time. Text 3 is of unknown date and provenance, although the hand looks 17th-century and resembles those of identified MacMhuirichs. The text preserves some details of legends associated with the ancestors of Clan MacLeod, which presumably circulated in a Scottish context.

supportDesc.condition: The condition is generally poor; loss or erosion of writing surface around the outer margins and tight binding along the inner margin frequently leads to loss of text.

layoutDesc.p: Verse is laid out with one couplet per manuscript line; prose is laid out in paragraphs.

history.summary: It is not known how the folios of Scottish provenance listed above came to end up in a Dillon duanaire. They appear to have been retained in a MacMhuirich milieu for a generation or so after Cathal's time, as Niall MacMhuirich (d. 1726) signs them in places.

langUsage.p: All three texts are in literary Early Modern Gaelic, with the poetry generally conformant with the standards of the Classical language. Neither archaisms nor influence from the vernacular are apparent, although, in terms of the latter, some aspects of Hand22’s spelling might repay further attention. An eclectic approach is taken to the different possibilities offered by the Classical language, with, for example, a mixture of synthetic and analytic verb forms and survival of the accusative, if largely just in prepositional phrases. This relaxed use of poetic and literary language resonates with the adventurous imagery and certain innovations in Cathal MacMhuirich’s style.

note.p: For discussion of this adjective, see Breatnach 1959/1960.

The foregoing seems to be the end of a digression noting two clans collateral to Clan MacLeod (Clann Dubsie and Clann Suain). These are presumably descended in some way from one or more of the sons of Olbur, with whom the pedigree proper now resumes.
In Skene's transcription from his lost Kilbride manuscript (c. 1540), this name appears as Magnus Aircin, which Skene takes as meaning "Magnus of Orkney" (Skene 1876: III, 461).
